      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "84053a47-32a6-4362-986b-b3a23e5de31f",
        "text": "The processes by which entities move from a more to a less centralized state vary. They can be initiated from the centers of authority (\"top-down ([[wikt:top-down]])\") or from individuals, localities or regions (\"bottom-up ([[Top-down and bottom-up design]])\"), or from a \"mutually desired\" combination of authorities and localities working together. Bottom-up decentralization usually stresses political values like local responsiveness and increased participation and tends to increase political stability. Top-down decentralization may be motivated by the desire to “shift deficits downwards” and find more resources to pay for services or pay off government debt.<ref name=Lkhagvadorj/>  Some hold that decentralization should not be imposed, but done in a respectful manner."
      },
